Sure! Here's an example of a C++ function called reverse_string that takes a string as input and returns the reversed string:

#include <iostream>
#include <string>

std::string reverse_string(const std::string& str) {
    std::string reversed_str;
    for (int i = str.length() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        reversed_str += str[i];
    }
    return reversed_str;
}

int main() {
    std::string input_str = "Hello, World!";
    std::string reversed_str = reverse_string(input_str);
    std::cout << "Reversed string: " << reversed_str << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
This function uses a for loop to iterate through the characters of the input string in reverse order and appends them to a new string called reversed_str. Finally, it returns the reversed string. In the main function, we provide an example input string "Hello, World!" and print the reversed string. You can modify the input_str variable to test the function with different strings.
